## §2h — Seed the tour by what the question asks, not by what scores loudest

A new one, found after I filed this issue, and it belongs in §2 with the rest of the ranking work. Your `runTour.ts` has both halves of this bug, unchanged from my old code.

**The symptom.** Asked how Excalidraw carries a user's edit *from pointer interaction through scene mutation, history, rendering, and collaboration or persistence*, the tour came back with **four renderers and a pointer handler** — two of the five seeds were one render function and its own throttled twin — and stamped `next: answer` on it. Mutation, history and persistence, three of the five layers the question *names*, were not in the payload at all. Sonnet went and found them itself: **21 further graph calls, 3.6M tokens**, on a question the tour claimed to have answered whole.

**Cause 1 — the stemmer only strips inflection.** Yours (`stemWord`) strips `ing`, `ed`, `es`, `s`, and then a prefix rule accepts a match at six shared characters. But a question is written in nouns and the code is written in verbs: "scene **mutation**" versus `**mutate**Element`. Those two share exactly five characters. The centre of the layer the question asked about matched *nothing*, so the set cover never had a candidate to cover that term with.

Strip the derivational suffixes as well, and trim a trailing `e`, so the noun in the question lands on the same stem as the verb in the code:

```ts
function stemWord(word: string): string {
  for (const suffix of ["ation","ing","ment","ence","ance","ion","ity","ed","es","s"]) {
    if (word.length > suffix.length + 3 && word.endsWith(suffix))
      return trimTrailingE(word.slice(0, -suffix.length));
  }
  return trimTrailingE(word);           // mutate -> mutat, mutation -> mutat
}
```

**Cause 2 — the cover's bonus stopped being decisive.** `diverseTourSeeds` adds a flat `coverage * 120` to the seed score. That was enough when seed scores topped out around 150. It is not enough once the score grows the reach term (§2a, +64) and the wider fan-out cap (§2b, +56): a *second renderer*, covering no new term at all, now outscores the first symbol of a layer nothing has covered yet. **If you take §2a and §2b, you must retune this or you will import my bug.**

> **Superseded — read the correction below before you implement this.** I first wrote "pick by coverage first, score only within a tier". That is wrong and I measured it: it hands seed slots to unimportant symbols that happen to match a rare word, and it cost me 87% → 58% on one axis. The rule that holds is to let coverage **multiply** the score:
>
> ```ts
> const value = item.score * (1 + 0.5 * coverage);   // quality is the gate, coverage the tiebreak
> ```
>
> A constant bonus is tuned against a score ceiling that moves; a factor is scale-free.

**Cause 3 — a seed that only restates a chosen one.** `renderNewElementScene` and `renderNewElementSceneThrottled` are one function and its throttle, and they took two of the five slots. Reject a candidate that sits in the same file and whose name a chosen seed already contains word for word:

```ts
function restates(chosen, candidate) {
  if (chosen.file !== candidate.file) return false;
  const a = subwords(chosen.name).map(stemWord), b = subwords(candidate.name).map(stemWord);
  const [short, long] = a.length <= b.length ? [a, b] : [b, a];
  return short.length > 0 && short.every((w, i) => long[i] === w);
}
```

**Result.** Same question, same repository: the seeds become `renderInteractiveScene`, `LinearElementEditor.handlePointerMoveInEditMode`, `Collab.componentDidMount`, **`mutateElement`**, **`History.perform`** — every layer the question named — in a payload *smaller* than before (24,808 vs 25,267 characters). Measured end to end on zod's shared question with gpt-5.6-sol: **96,666 tokens in 3 calls → 75,088 in 2**, and the saving against the no-MCP baseline goes 86% → 89%.

**What it does not do, and why I am telling you.** I diffed the seeds across the whole corpus (16 repo × prompt-family combinations) before believing it. Four are unchanged; twelve move. Most of the movement is plainly right — TypeORM's find-options question now seeds `applyFindOptions` and `joinEagerRelations`, RxJS drops an unrelated ajax body serializer, Excalidraw stops seeding the same symbol twice. But at least two look like they may have got *worse*, and I am re-measuring those cells rather than assuming. **A ranking change is not a free win; diff the seeds on every repository you have, and measure the ones that move.** The set-cover reordering is exactly the kind of change that fixes the case you looked at and quietly costs you two you did not.
